Use sqlcmd (SQL Server command-line tool) to configure managed identity database roles.
Do NOT use Python scripts for SQL execution.

Add the following commands to deploy-infra/README.md for Step 7 (Configure Database Roles for Managed Identity):

```powershell
$managedIdentityName = (az deployment group show --resource-group $resourceGroup --name main --query "properties.outputs.managedIdentityName.value" -o tsv)
$sqlServerName = (az deployment group show --resource-group $resourceGroup --name main --query "properties.outputs.sqlServerName.value" -o tsv)

# Create the managed identity user and grant roles using sqlcmd with Azure AD auth
sqlcmd -S "$sqlServerName.database.windows.net" -d "Northwind" -G -Q "IF EXISTS (SELECT * FROM sys.database_principals WHERE name = '$managedIdentityName') BEGIN DROP USER [$managedIdentityName]; END"
sqlcmd -S "$sqlServerName.database.windows.net" -d "Northwind" -G -Q "CREATE USER [$managedIdentityName] FROM EXTERNAL PROVIDER;"
sqlcmd -S "$sqlServerName.database.windows.net" -d "Northwind" -G -Q "ALTER ROLE db_datareader ADD MEMBER [$managedIdentityName];"
sqlcmd -S "$sqlServerName.database.windows.net" -d "Northwind" -G -Q "ALTER ROLE db_datawriter ADD MEMBER [$managedIdentityName];"
sqlcmd -S "$sqlServerName.database.windows.net" -d "Northwind" -G -Q "GRANT EXECUTE TO [$managedIdentityName];"
```

The -G flag enables Azure Active Directory authentication using the currently logged-in Azure CLI credentials.
The -Q flag executes a single query and exits.

Do NOT create script.sql files that require sed substitution - use PowerShell variable expansion directly in the sqlcmd commands instead.


